07/09/2004
BELGRADE, Serbia-Montenegro -- The head of Serbia-Montenegro's national council for co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal, Rasim Ljajic, arrives in The Hague on Tuesday (7 September). 
Prior to his visit, he said Belgrade is prepared to hand over indictee Ratko Mladic if he turns up in Serbia.
In other news, the trial of Milorad Lukovic "Legija" and 12 other people charged with the assassination of Serbian Prime Minister Zoran Djindjic resumed at the Belgrade District Court on Monday after repeated delays. 
Legija answered questions by defence lawyers and an attorney representing Djindjic's family. 
The former paramilitary leader has explicitly denied any role in the murder. 
(Tanjug, Danas - 07/09/04; Beta, SRNA, AP - 06/09/04)
